# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: password-hashing-argon2
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] The Argon2 function uses a large, fixed-size memory region (often called the 'memory array' in documentation) to make brute-force attacks computationally expensive.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] While there is no public cryptanalysis applicable to Argon2d, there are two published attacks on the Argon2i function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] The first attack is applicable only to the old version of Argon2i, while the second has been extended to the latest version (1.3).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] The first attack shows that it is possible to compute a single-pass Argon2i function using between a quarter and a fifth of the desired space with no time penalty, and compute a multiple-pass Argon2i using only N/e (≈ N/2.72) space with no time penalty.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] According to the Argon2 authors, this attack vector was fixed in version 1.3.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] The second attack shows that Argon2i can be computed by an algorithm which has complexity O(n7/4 log(n)) for all choices of parameters σ (space cost), τ (time cost), and thread-count such that n=σ∗τ.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] The Argon2 authors claim that this attack is not efficient if Argon2i is used with three or more passes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] However, Joël Alwen and Jeremiah Blocki improved the attack and showed that in order for the attack to fail, Argon2i v1.3 needs more than 10 passes over memory.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] To address these concerns, RFC9106 recommends using Argon2id to largely mitigate such attacks.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] Argon2 makes use of a hash function capable of producing digests up to 232 bytes long.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/argon2] This hash function is internally built upon Blake2.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The bcrypt function is the default password hash algorithm for OpenBSD, and was the default for some Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] There are implementations of bcrypt in C, C++, C#, Embarcadero Delphi, Elixir, Go, Java, JavaScript, Perl, PHP, Ruby, Python, Rust, V (Vlang), Zig and other languages.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Blowfish is notable among block ciphers for its expensive key setup phase.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] It starts off with subkeys in a standard state, then uses this state to perform a block encryption using part of the key, and uses the result of that encryption (which is more accurate at hashing) to replace some of the subkeys.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Then it uses this modified state to encrypt another part of the key, and uses the result to replace more of the subkeys.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] It proceeds in this fashion, using a progressively modified state to hash the key and replace bits of state, until all subkeys have been set.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Provos and Mazières took advantage of this, and took it further.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] They developed a new key setup algorithm for Blowfish, dubbing the resulting cipher "Eksblowfish" ("expensive key schedule Blowfish").
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The key setup begins with a modified form of the standard Blowfish key setup, in which both the salt and password are used to set all subkeys.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] There are then a number of rounds in which the standard Blowfish keying algorithm is applied, using alternatively the salt and the password as the key, each round starting with the subkey state from the previous round.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] In theory, this is no stronger than the standard Blowfish key schedule, but the number of rekeying rounds is configurable; this process can therefore be made arbitrarily slow, which helps deter brute-force attacks upon the hash or salt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The input to the bcrypt function is the password string (up to 72 bytes), a numeric cost, and a 16-byte (128-bit) salt value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The bcrypt function uses these inputs to compute a 24-byte (192-bit) hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The base-64 encoding in bcrypt uses the table `./ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789`, which differs from RFC 4648 Base64 encoding.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The original bcrypt specification defined a prefix of `$2$`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The original specification did not define how to handle non-ASCII characters, nor how to handle a null terminator.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] With this change, the version was changed to `$2a$`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] In June 2011, a bug was discovered in **crypt_blowfish**, a PHP implementation of bcrypt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] It was mis-handling characters with the 8th bit set.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] They suggested that system administrators update their existing password database, replacing `$2a$` with `$2x$`, to indicate that those hashes are bad (and need to use the old broken algorithm).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] They also suggested the idea of having **crypt_blowfish** emit `$2y$` for hashes generated by the fixed algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Nobody else, including Canonical and OpenBSD, adopted the idea of 2x/2y.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] This version marker change was limited to **crypt_blowfish**.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] A bug was discovered in the OpenBSD implementation of bcrypt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] It was using an unsigned 8-bit value to hold the length of the password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] For passwords longer than 255 bytes, instead of being truncated at 72 bytes the password would be truncated at the lesser of 72 or the length modulo 256.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] For example, a 260 byte password would be truncated at 4 bytes rather than truncated at 72 bytes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] When OpenBSD fixed this issue, they changed the version to `$2b$`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The bcrypt function below encrypts the text *"OrpheanBeholderScryDoubt"* 64 times using Blowfish.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] InitialState works as in the original Blowfish algorithm, populating the P-array and S-box entries with the fractional part of $\pi$ in hexadecimal.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Hence, `ExpandKey(*state*, *key*, 0)` is the same as regular Blowfish key schedule since all XORs with the all-zero salt value are ineffectual.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] `ExpandKey(*state*, *salt*, 0)` is similar, but uses the salt as a 128-bit key.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Many implementations of bcrypt truncate the password to the first 72 bytes, following the OpenBSD implementation.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The mathematical algorithm itself requires initialization with 18 32-bit subkeys (equivalent to 72 octets/bytes).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The original specification of bcrypt does not mandate any one particular method for mapping text-based passwords from userland into numeric values for the algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Note that the quote above mentions passwords "up to 56 bytes" even though the algorithm itself makes use of a 72 byte initial value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Implementations have varied in their approach of converting passwords into initial numeric values, including sometimes reducing the strength of passwords containing non-ASCII characters.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Bcrypt is not a key derivation function (KDF).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] For example, bcrypt cannot be used to derive a 512-bit key from a password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] At the same time, algorithms like pbkdf2, scrypt, and argon2 *are* password-based key derivation functions - where the output is then used for the purpose of password hashing rather than just key derivation.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] Password hashing generally needs to complete < 1000 ms.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] In this scenario, bcrypt is stronger than pbkdf2, scrypt, and argon2.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] bcrypt has a maximum password length of 72 bytes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The password (which is UTF-8 encoded), is repeated until it is 72-bytes long.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] In the worst case a password is limited to 18 characters, when every character requires 4 bytes of UTF-8 encoding.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] In 2024 a single-sign-on service by Okta, Inc. announced a vulnerability due to the password being concatenated after the username and the pair hashed with bcrypt, resulting in the password being ignored for logins with a long-enough username.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] It is unclear why the canonical implementation deletes 8-bits from the resulting password hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] The encoding used by the canonical OpenBSD implementation uses the same Base64 alphabet as crypt, an atypical Base64 alphabet.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/bcrypt] As such, the encoding is not compatible with the more common RFC 4648 Base64 encoding.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet advises you on the proper methods for storing passwords for authentication.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When passwords are stored, they must be protected from an attacker even if the application or database is compromised.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Fortunately, a majority of modern languages and frameworks provide built-in functionality to help store passwords safely.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should never be stored in plain text.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Instead, they must be protected using strong, slow hashing algorithms such as Argon2id, bcrypt, or PBKDF2.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] A unique salt must be added to each password to prevent attackers from using precomputed lookup tables like rainbow tables.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Fast hashing algorithms such as SHA‑256 are not suitable for password storage because they allow attackers to perform large numbers of guesses quickly.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Using slow, memory‑hard algorithms makes brute‑force attacks significantly more difficult, expensive, and time‑consuming.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Because **hashing is a one-way function** (i.e., it is impossible to "decrypt" a hash and obtain the original plaintext value), it is the most appropriate approach for password validation.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Even if an attacker obtains the hashed password, they cannot use it to log in as the victim.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Since **encryption is a two-way function**, attackers can retrieve the original plaintext from the encrypted data.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It can be used to store data such as a user's address since this data is displayed in plaintext on the user's profile.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Hashing their address would result in a garbled mess.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The only time encryption should be used in passwords is in edge cases where it is necessary to obtain the original plaintext password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This might be necessary if the application needs to use the password to authenticate with another system that does not support a modern way to programmatically grant access, such as OpenID Connect (OIDC).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, an alternative architecture should be used to avoid the need to store passwords in an encrypted form.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For further guidance on encryption, see the Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] While the number of permutations can be enormous, with high speed hardware (such as GPUs) and cloud services with many servers for rent, the cost to an attacker is relatively small to do successful password cracking, especially when best practices for hashing are not followed.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] A salt is a unique, randomly generated string that is added to each password as part of the hashing process.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] As the salt is unique for every user, an attacker has to crack hashes one at a time using the respective salt rather than calculating a hash once and comparing it against every stored hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This makes cracking large numbers of hashes significantly harder, as the time required grows in direct proportion to the number of hashes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Salting also protects against an attacker's pre-computing hashes using rainbow tables or database-based lookups.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Finally, salting means that it is impossible to determine whether two users have the same password without cracking the hashes, as the different salts will result in different hashes even if the passwords are the same.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] At the algorithm and specification level, modern password hashing functions such as Argon2id, bcrypt, and PBKDF2 require the caller to provide a salt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, most widely used implementations and libraries automatically generate and manage salts internally, so application developers typically do not need to handle salt generation manually when using these libraries correctly.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Peppering is a class of strategies that can be used in addition to salting to provide an additional layer of protection.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It prevents an attacker from being able to crack any of the hashes if they only have access to the database, for example, if they have exploited a SQL injection vulnerability or obtained a backup of the database.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this strategy, a pepper is added to a password before being hashed by a password hashing algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The computed hash is then stored in the database.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this case the pepper should be a random value generated securely.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] See the Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet for more information on securely generating random values.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this strategy, a password is hashed as usual using a password hashing algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The resulting password hash is then hashed again using an HMAC (e.g., HMAC-SHA256, HMAC-SHA512, depending on the desired output length) before storing the resulting hash in the database.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this case the pepper is acting as the HMAC key and should be generated as per requirements of the HMAC algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor is the number of iterations of the hashing algorithm that are performed for each password (usually, it's actually `2^work` iterations).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor is typically stored in the hash output.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It makes calculating the hash more computationally expensive, which in turn reduces the speed and/or increases the cost for which an attacker can attempt to crack the password hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When you choose a work factor, strike a balance between security and performance.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Though higher work factors make hashes more difficult for an attacker to crack, they will slow down the process of verifying a login attempt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If the work factor is too high, the performance of the application may be degraded, which could be used by an attacker to carry out a denial of service attack by exhausting the server's CPU with a large number of login attempts.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] There is no golden rule for the ideal work factor - it will depend on the performance of the server and the number of users on the application.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Determining the optimal work factor will require experimentation on the specific server(s) used by the application.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] As a general rule, calculating a hash should take less than one second.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] One key advantage of having a work factor is that it can be increased over time as hardware becomes more powerful and cheaper.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The most common approach to upgrading the work factor is to wait until the user next authenticates, then re-hash their password with the new work factor.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The different hashes will have different work factors and hashes may never be upgraded if the user doesn't log back into the application.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the application, it may be appropriate to remove the older password hashes and require users to reset their passwords next time they need to login in order to avoid storing older and less secure hashes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Some modern hashing algorithms have been specifically designed to securely store passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that they should be slow (unlike algorithms such as MD5 and SHA-1, which were designed to be fast), and you can change how slow they are by changing the work factor.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] You do not need to hide which password hashing algorithm is used by an application.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If you utilize a modern password hashing algorithm with proper configuration parameters, it should be safe to state in public which password hashing algorithms are in use and be listed here.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When selecting a password hashing algorithm, developers should prefer modern algorithms that are designed to resist both GPU-based and memory-based attacks.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, newer algorithms should be chosen for new applications, while older algorithms may still be acceptable for legacy systems with appropriate configuration.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Three hashing algorithms that should be considered.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Argon2 was the winner of the 2015 Password Hashing Competition.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Out of the three Argon2 versions, use the Argon2id variant since it provides a balanced approach to resisting both side-channel and GPU-based attacks.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Rather than a simple work factor like other algorithms, Argon2id has three different parameters that can be configured: the base minimum of the minimum memory size (m), the minimum number of iterations (t), and the degree of parallelism (p).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These parameters control how computationally expensive it is to compute a password hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Increasing memory usage, iteration count, or parallelism makes password cracking attempts significantly slower and more costly for attackers, while still remaining practical for legitimate authentication requests when tuned appropriately.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings provide an equal level of defense, and the only difference is a trade off between CPU and RAM usage.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] scrypt is a password-based key derivation function created by Colin Percival.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] While Argon2id should be the best choice for password hashing, scrypt should be used when the former is not available.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Like Argon2id, scrypt has three parameters that can be configured: the minimum memory cost parameter (N), the blocksize (r), and the degree of parallelism (p).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings provide a similar minimal level of defense, with the main trade-off between parallelism and RAM usage.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The bcrypt password hashing function **should only** be used for password storage in legacy systems where Argon2 and scrypt are not available.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor should be as large as verification server performance will allow, with a minimum of 10.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] bcrypt has a maximum length input length of 72 bytes for most implementations, so you should enforce a maximum password length of 72 bytes (or less if the bcrypt implementation in use has smaller limits).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] An alternative approach is to pre-hash the user-supplied password with a fast algorithm such as SHA-2, HMAC, or BLAKE3 and then to hash the resulting hash value with bcrypt (i.e., `bcrypt(H($password)), $salt, $cost)`)..
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This can be **dangerous** because of null bytes in the hash output value and because of password shucking.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The original bcrypt expects a null terminated password string, this means that the hash value will only be used to the first null byte in the hash value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Password shucking uses the fact, that it is easy to check if `bcrypt(base64(H($password))), $salt, $cost) == bcrypt(base64($leaked_hash), $salt, $cost)`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If the inner hash function `H` is used with the same password somewhere else and known to an attacker cracking the password can be reduced to breaking the hash function `H`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] `bcrypt(base64(sha512($password))), $salt, $cost)`) is a **dangerous practice** and is as secure as just using pure SHA-512.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Password shucking only works if a leaked hash is known to the attacker, either through a breach database or rainbow tables.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] To mitigate password shucking a pepper can be used.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] To summarize if bcrypt has to be used and the password should to be pre-hashed you should do `bcrypt(base64(hmac-sha384(data:$password, key:$pepper)), $salt, $cost)` and store the pepper not in the database.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Since PBKDF2 is recommended by NIST and has FIPS-140 validated implementations, it should be the preferred algorithm when these are required.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The PBKDF2 algorithm requires that you select an internal hashing algorithm such as an HMAC or a variety of other hashing algorithms.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] HMAC-SHA-256 is widely supported and is recommended by NIST.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor for PBKDF2 is implemented through an iteration count, which should be set differently based on the internal hashing algorithm used.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings are equivalent in the defense they provide.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When PBKDF2 is used with an HMAC, and the password is longer than the hash function's block size (64 bytes for SHA-256), the password will be automatically pre-hashed.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, the password "This is a password longer than 512 bits which is the block size of SHA-256" is converted to the hash value (in hex): `fa91498c139805af73f7ba275cca071e78d78675027000c99a9925e2ec92eedd`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Good implementations of PBKDF2 perform pre-hashing before the expensive iterated hashing phase.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, some implementations perform the conversion on each iteration, which can make hashing long passwords significantly more expensive than hashing short passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When users supply very long passwords, a potential denial of service vulnerability could occur, such as the one published in Django during 2013.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Manual pre-hashing can reduce this risk but requires adding a salt to the pre-hash step.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Older applications that use less secure hashing algorithms, such as MD5 or SHA-1, can be upgraded to modern password hashing algorithms as described above.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When the users enter their password (usually by authenticating on the application), that input should be re-hashed using the new algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Defenders should expire the users' current password and require them to enter a new one, so that any older (less secure) hashes of their password are no longer useful to an attacker.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, this means that old (less secure) password hashes will be stored in the database until the user logs in.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] You can take one of two approaches to avoid this dilemma.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Upgrade Method One: Expire and delete the password hashes of users who have been inactive for an extended period and require them to reset their passwords to login again.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Although secure, this approach is not particularly user-friendly.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Expiring the passwords of many users may cause issues for support staff or may be interpreted by users as an indication of a breach.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Upgrade Method Two: Use the existing password hashes as inputs for a more secure algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the application originally stored passwords as `md5($password)`, this could be easily upgraded to `bcrypt(md5($password))`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Layering the hashes avoids the need to know the original password; however, it can make the hashes easier to crack.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These hashes should be replaced with direct hashes of the users' passwords next time the user logs in.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Remember that once your password hashing method is selected, it will have to be upgraded in the future, so ensure that upgrading your hashing algorithm is as easy as possible.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] During the transition period, allow for a mix of old and new hashing algorithms.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Using a mix of hashing algorithms is easier if the password hashing algorithm and work factor are stored with the password using a standard format, for example, the modular PHC string format.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Your hashing library must be able to accept a wide range of characters and should be compatible with all Unicode codepoints, so users can use the full range of characters available on modern devices - especially mobile keyboards.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] They should be able to select passwords from various languages and include pictograms.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Prior to hashing the entropy of the user's entry should not be reduced, and password hashing libraries need to be able to use input that may contain a NULL byte.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] A **rainbow table** is a precomputed table for caching the outputs of a cryptographic hash function, usually for cracking password hashes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Passwords are typically stored not in plain text form, but as hash values.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If such a database of hashed passwords falls into the hands of attackers, they can use a precomputed rainbow table to recover the plaintext passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] A common defense against this attack is to compute the hashes using a key derivation function that adds a "salt" to each password before hashing it, with different passwords receiving different salts, which are stored in plain text along with the hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables are a practical example of a space–time tradeoff: they use less computer processing time and more storage than a brute-force attack which calculates a hash on every attempt, but more processing time and less storage than a simple table that stores the hash of every possible password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables were invented by Philippe Oechslin as an application of an earlier, simpler algorithm by Martin Hellman.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] For user authentication, passwords are stored either as plaintext or hashes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Since passwords stored as plaintext are easily stolen if database access is compromised, databases typically store hashes instead.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Thus, no one – including the authentication system – can learn a password merely by looking at the value stored in the database.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] When a user enters a password for authentication, a hash is computed for it and then compared to the stored hash for that user.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Authentication fails if the two hashes do not match; moreover, authentication would equally fail if a hashed value were entered as a password, since the authentication system would hash it a second time.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] To learn a password from a hash is to find a string which, when input into the hash function, creates that same hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This is the same as inverting the hash function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Though brute-force attacks (e.g. dictionary attacks) may be used to try to invert a hash function, they can become infeasible when the set of possible passwords is large enough.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] An alternative to brute-force is to use precomputed hash chain tables.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables are a special kind of such table that overcome certain technical difficulties.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The term *rainbow tables* was first used in Oechslin's initial paper.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The term refers to the way different reduction functions are used to increase the success rate of the attack.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The original method by Hellman uses many small tables with a different reduction function in each.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables are much bigger and use a different reduction function in each column.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] When colors are used to represent the reduction functions, a rainbow appears in the rainbow table.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Figure 2 of Oechslin's paper contains a black-and-white graphic that illustrates how these sections are related.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] For his presentation at the Crypto 2003 conference, Oechslin added color to the graphic in order to make the rainbow association more clear.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The enhanced graphic that was presented at the conference is shown in the illustration.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Given a password hash function H and a finite set of passwords P, the goal is to precompute a data structure that, given any output *h* of the hash function, can either locate an element *p* in P such that H(*p*) = *h*, or determine that there is no such *p* in P.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The simplest way to do this is compute H(*p*) for all *p* in P, but then storing the table requires Θ(|P|*n*) bits of space, where |P| is the size of the set P and *n* is the size of an output of H, which is prohibitive for large |P|.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Hash chains are a technique for decreasing this space requirement.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The idea is to define a *reduction function* R that maps hash values back into values in P.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Note, however, that the reduction function is not actually an inverse of the hash function, but rather a different function with a swapped domain and codomain of the hash function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] By alternating the hash function with the reduction function, *chains* of alternating passwords and hash values are formed.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The only requirement for the reduction function is to be able to return a "plain text" value in a specific size.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] To generate the table, we choose a random set of *initial passwords* from P, compute chains of some fixed length *k* for each one, and store *only* the first and last password in each chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The first password is called the *starting point* and the last one is called the *endpoint*.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] In the example chain above, "aaaaaa" would be the starting point and "kiebgt" would be the endpoint, and none of the other passwords (or the hash values) would be stored.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Now, given a hash value *h* to invert (find the corresponding password for), compute a chain starting with *h* by applying R, then H, then R, and so on.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If at any point a value matches one of the endpoints in the table, the corresponding starting point allows to recreate the complete chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] There's a high chance that this chain will contain the value *h*, and if so, the immediately preceding value in the chain is the password *p* that we seek.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Thus, the password is "sgfnyd" (or a different password that has the same hash value).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Note however that this chain does not *always* contain the hash value *h*; it may so happen that the chain starting at *h* merges with a chain having a different starting point.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The chain generated by the corresponding starting password "aaaaaa" is then followed until FB107E70 is reached.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The search will end without reaching FB107E70 because this value is not contained in the chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] In this case, the match is ignored and the chain of *h* is extended looking for another match.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If the chain of *h* gets extended to length *k* with no good matches, then the password was never produced in any of the chains.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The table content does not depend on the hash value to be inverted.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] It is created once and then repeatedly used for the lookups unmodified.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Increasing the length of the chain decreases the size of the table.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] However, it also increases the time required to perform lookups, and this is the time-memory trade-off of the rainbow table.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] In a simple case of one-item chains, the lookup is very fast, but the table is very big.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Once chains get longer, the lookup slows, but the table size goes down.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Most serious if at any point two chains *collide* (produce the same value), they will merge and consequently the table will not cover as many passwords despite having paid the same computational cost to generate.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Because previous chains are not stored in their entirety, this is impossible to detect efficiently.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] For example, if the third value in chain 3 matches the second value in chain 7, the two chains will cover almost the same sequence of values, but their final values will not be the same.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The hash function H is unlikely to produce collisions as it is usually considered an important security feature not to do so, but the reduction function R, because of its need to correctly cover the likely plaintexts, cannot be collision resistant.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Other difficulties result from the importance of choosing the correct function for R.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Picking R to be the identity is little better than a brute force approach.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Only when the attacker has a good idea of likely plaintexts will they be able to choose a function R that makes sure time and space are only used for likely plaintexts, not the entire space of possible passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Also it can be difficult to design the function R to match the expected distribution of plaintexts.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables effectively solve the problem of collisions with ordinary hash chains by replacing the single reduction function R with a sequence of related reduction functions R1 through R*k*.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] In this way, for two chains to collide and merge they must hit the same value *on the same iteration*: consequently, the final values in these chains will be identical.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] A final postprocessing pass can sort the chains in the table and remove any "duplicate" chains that have the same final values as other chains.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] New chains are then generated to fill out the table.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] These chains are not *collision-free* (they may overlap briefly) but they will not merge, drastically reducing the overall number of collisions.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Using sequences of reduction functions changes how lookup is done: because the hash value of interest may be found at any location in the chain, it's necessary to generate *k* different chains.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This creates a new way of producing a false alarm: an incorrect "guess" of the position of the hash value may needlessly evaluate a chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables can achieve similar performance with tables that are *k* times larger, allowing them to perform a factor of *k* fewer lookups.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If the test fails (*rambo* doesn't appear in the table), one computes a chain with the two last reductions (these two reductions are represented at step 2) Note: If this new test fails again, one continues with 3 reductions, 4 reductions, etc. until the password is found.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If no chain contains the password, then the attack has failed.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] If this test is positive (step 3, *linux23* appears at the end of the chain and in the table), the password is retrieved at the beginning of the chain that produces *linux23*.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Here we find *passwd* at the beginning of the corresponding chain stored in the table.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] At this point (step 4), one generates a chain and compares at each iteration the hash with the target hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] We find the hash *re3xes* in the chain, and the password that produced it (*culture*) one step earlier in the chain: the attack is successful.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables use a refined algorithm with a different reduction function for each "link" in a chain, so that when there is a hash collision in two or more chains, the chains will not merge as long as the collision doesn't occur at the same position in each chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This increases the probability of a correct crack for a given table size, at the cost of squaring the number of steps required per lookup, as the lookup routine now also needs to iterate through the index of the first reduction function used in the chain.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables are specific to the hash function they were created for e.g., MD5 tables can crack only MD5 hashes.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The theory of this technique was invented by Philippe Oechslin as a fast form of time/memory tradeoff, which he implemented in the Windows password cracker Ophcrack.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The more powerful RainbowCrack program was later developed that can generate and use rainbow tables for a variety of character sets and hashing algorithms, including LM hash, MD5, and SHA-1.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Thus the 8-character lowercase alphanumeric passwords case (|*P*| ≃ 3×1012) would be easily tractable with a personal computer while the 16-character lowercase alphanumeric passwords case (|*P*| ≃ 1025) would be completely intractable.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] A rainbow table is ineffective against one-way hashes that include large salts.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The salt value is not secret and may be generated at random and stored with the password hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] A large salt value prevents precomputation attacks, including rainbow tables, by ensuring that each user's password is hashed uniquely.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This means that two users with the same password will have different password hashes (assuming different salts are used).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] In order to succeed, an attacker needs to precompute tables for each possible salt value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The salt must be large enough, otherwise an attacker can make a table for each salt value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] For older Unix passwords which used a 12-bit salt this would require 4096 tables, a significant increase in cost for the attacker, but not impractical with terabyte hard drives.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The SHA2-crypt and bcrypt methods—used in Linux, BSD Unixes, and Solaris—have salts of 128 bits.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] These larger salt values make precomputation attacks against these systems infeasible for almost any length of a password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Even if the attacker could generate a million tables per second, they would still need billions of years to generate tables for all possible salts.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Another technique that helps prevent precomputation attacks is key stretching.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] When stretching is used, the salt, password, and some intermediate hash values are run through the underlying hash function multiple times to increase the computation time required to hash each password.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] For instance, MD5-Crypt uses a 1000 iteration loop that repeatedly feeds the salt, password, and current intermediate hash value back into the underlying MD5 hash function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The user's password hash is the concatenation of the salt value (which is not secret) and the final hash.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The extra time is not noticeable to users because they have to wait only a fraction of a second each time they log in.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] On the other hand, stretching reduces the effectiveness of brute-force attacks in proportion to the number of iterations because it reduces the number of attempts an attacker can perform in a given time frame.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This principle is applied in MD5-Crypt and in bcrypt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] It also greatly increases the time needed to build a precomputed table, but in the absence of salt, this needs only to be done once.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, deploys two salts, one public and one secret, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the secret salt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the secret salt value.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The secret salt size is chosen so that the brute force search is imperceptible to the legitimate user.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] However, it makes the rainbow dictionary needed by the attacker much larger.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables and other precomputation attacks do not work against passwords that contain symbols outside the range presupposed, or that are longer than those precomputed by the attacker.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] However, tables can be generated that take into account common ways in which users attempt to choose more secure passwords, such as adding a number or special character.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Because of the sizable investment in computing processing, rainbow tables beyond fourteen places in length are not yet common.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] So, choosing a password that is longer than fourteen characters may force an attacker to resort to brute-force methods.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Specific intensive efforts focused on LM hash, an older hash algorithm used by Microsoft, are publicly available.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] LM hash is particularly vulnerable because passwords longer than 7 characters are broken into two sections, each of which is hashed separately.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Choosing a password that is fifteen characters or longer guarantees that an LM hash will not be generated.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Nearly all distributions and variations of Unix, Linux, and BSD use hashes with salts, though many applications use just a hash (typically MD5) with no salt.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] The Microsoft Windows NT/2000 family uses the LAN Manager and NT LAN Manager hashing method (based on MD4) and is also unsalted, which makes it one of the most popularly generated tables.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] Rainbow tables have seen reduced usage as of 2020 as salting is more common and GPU-based brute force attacks have become more practical.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/rainbow-table] However, rainbow tables are available for eight and nine character NTLM passwords.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] In cryptography, **scrypt** (pronounced "ess crypt") is a password-based key derivation function created by Colin Percival in March 2009, originally for the Tarsnap online backup service.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] The algorithm was specifically designed to make it costly to perform large-scale custom hardware attacks by requiring large amounts of memory.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] In 2016, the scrypt algorithm was published by IETF as RFC 7914.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] A simplified version of scrypt is used as a proof-of-work scheme by a number of cryptocurrencies, first implemented by an anonymous programmer called ArtForz in Tenebrix and followed by Fairbrix and Litecoin soon after.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] A password-based key derivation function (password-based KDF) is generally designed to be computationally intensive, so that it takes a relatively long time to compute (say on the order of several hundred milliseconds).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Legitimate users only need to perform the function once per operation (e.g., authentication), and so the time required is negligible.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] However, a brute-force attack would likely need to perform the operation billions of times, at which point the time requirements become significant and, ideally, prohibitive.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Previous password-based KDFs (such as the popular PBKDF2 from RSA Laboratories) have relatively low resource demands, meaning they do not require elaborate hardware or very much memory to perform.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] They are therefore easily and cheaply implemented in hardware (for instance on an ASIC or even an FPGA).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] This allows an attacker with sufficient resources to launch a large-scale parallel attack by building hundreds or even thousands of implementations of the algorithm in hardware and having each search a different subset of the key space.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] This divides the amount of time needed to complete a brute-force attack by the number of implementations available, very possibly bringing it down to a reasonable time frame.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] The scrypt function is designed to hinder such attempts by raising the resource demands of the algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] The large memory requirements of scrypt come from a large vector of pseudorandom bit strings that are generated as part of the algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Once the vector is generated, the elements of it are accessed in a pseudo-random order and combined to produce the derived key.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] A straightforward implementation would need to keep the entire vector in RAM so that it can be accessed as needed.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Because the elements of the vector are generated algorithmically, each element could be generated *on the fly* as needed, only storing one element in memory at a time and therefore cutting the memory requirements significantly.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] However, the generation of each element is intended to be computationally expensive, and the elements are expected to be accessed many times throughout the execution of the function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Thus there is a significant trade-off in speed to get rid of the large memory requirements.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] This sort of time–memory trade-off often exists in computer algorithms: speed can be increased at the cost of using more memory, or memory requirements decreased at the cost of performing more operations and taking longer.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] The idea behind scrypt is to deliberately make this trade-off costly in either direction.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Where *`PBKDF2(P, S, c, dkLen)`* notation is defined in RFC 2898, where c is an iteration count.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] This notation is used by RFC 7914 for specifying a usage of PBKDF2 with c = 1.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Where RFC 7914 defines `Integerify(X)` as the result of interpreting the last 64 bytes of X as a *little-endian* integer A1.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Since Iterations equals 2 to the power of N, only the *first* `Ceiling(N / 8)` bytes among the *last* 64 bytes of X, interpreted as a *little-endian* integer A2, are actually needed to compute `Integerify(X) mod Iterations = A1 mod Iterations = A2 mod Iterations`.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Where *Salsa20/8* is the 8-round version of Salsa20.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Scrypt is used in many cryptocurrencies as a proof-of-work algorithm (more precisely, as the hash function in the Hashcash proof-of-work algorithm).
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] It was first implemented for Tenebrix (released in September 2011) and served as the basis for Litecoin and Dogecoin, which also adopted its scrypt algorithm.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] Mining of cryptocurrencies that use scrypt is often performed on graphics processing units (GPUs) since GPUs tend to have significantly more processing power (for some algorithms) compared to the CPU.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] This led to shortages of high end GPUs due to the rising price of these currencies in the months of November and December 2013.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] The scrypt utility was written in May 2009 by Colin Percival as a demonstration of the scrypt key derivation function.
[src:password-hashing-argon2/scrypt] It's available in most Linux and BSD distributions.
